# Rotation Drill (#143)

## Objective
Teach the three-call rotation system (hedge/rotate/trap) that activates when a ball handler beats their defender in man-to-man defense.

## Setup
- Half court
- 3 offensive players (1, 3, 4) and 3 defenders (X1, X3, X4)
- Coach passes to initiate the drill
- Players rotate through positions 1, 3, 4, X1, X3, X4

<!-- DIAGRAM: Player 1 with ball on the left wing dribbling toward basket, X1 beaten. X4 slides across the lane (from near the low block) to stop ball. Player 3 is at the right wing, X3 at mid-lane. Player 4 near ball-side block. -->

## Execution
1. Coach passes to player 1, who drives by defender X1 on either side.
2. X4, seeing player 1 become a breakaway dribbler, makes one of three calls:
   - **"Hedge"** — X4 believes X1 can recover; all defenders keep their assignments.
   - **"Rotate"** — X4 slides across the lane to stop the ball; X3 immediately rotates down to cover the basket area (player 4 is cutting for a layup pass); X1 recovers to cover X3's assignment (player 3).
   - **"Trap"** — X4 and X1 trap the ball handler together; X3 plays interception stance between players 3 and 4, shading toward 4 near the basket. If a pass escapes the trap: X3 takes the pass receiver, X1 stays on player 1, X4 sprints to cover the remaining open player.
3. If player 1 drives left, X3 is first responsible to close the gap; if X3 cannot stop it, X4 calls "rotate."
4. Players rotate after each offensive player has played positions 1, 3, and 4 and each defender has played X1, X3, and X4.

## Coaching Points
- **X4 must make a decisive call immediately** — hesitation allows a layup.
- Rotation must be activated quickly enough to stop the ball OUTSIDE the lane.
- X3 must read X4's call and sprint to the basket before player 4 arrives.
- Ball-side defense (before the drive) is always denial + fence slide; X1 should not be beaten easily.
- Make drills more demanding than game conditions — "you want to make your drills more demanding than actual game conditions." [S15, p.297]

## Progressions
1. **Beginner**: Walk through the rotation; X1 allows the drive passively so defenders can learn the rotation assignment. Only run the standard "rotate" call.
2. **Intermediate** (base drill): X1 attempts to deny the pass to player 1 first (fence slide/deny-wing technique), then player 1 drives live. X4 calls hedge, rotate, or trap.
3. **Advanced**: Allow player 1 and X1 to play full 1-on-1 until player 1 creates separation or drives either side. On a successful rotation, extend to live 3-on-3 — all aspects of motion offense and man-to-man defense come into play. [S15, p.298]

